Existing medical devices primarily rely on reactive runtime diagnostics and post-failure troubleshooting for identifying embedded software instability and performance degradation. Current systems generally monitor static resource thresholds such as CPU and memory usage but do not effectively detect progressive runtime degradation trends including memory growth, latency drift, thread starvation, communication bottlenecks, or correlated subsystem instability.

As medical devices become increasingly software-driven and operate continuously for extended durations, intelligent runtime optimization and predictive stability analysis become important for improving reliability and reducing downtime.

The proposed invention introduces an AI-assisted runtime optimization framework capable of identifying abnormal runtime behavior and degradation trends before visible subsystem instability or software failure occurs.
